          "body": "The chapter opens with a catalogue of overwhelming force: Ben-hadad, thirty-two vassal kings, horses, chariots — a coalition army that dwarfs anything Israel could field. Ahab's first response is capitulation so complete it is almost a satire of weakness: 'I am yours, and all that I have' (20:4). When Ben-hadad escalates his demands, the elders counsel resistance and Ahab consults them — but neither Ahab nor his elders consult the LORD. The entire first twelve verses proceed as if the God of Israel is not a party to the crisis. This political vacuum is exactly the environment in which the prophetic word arrives with maximum impact in verse 13. The contrast between the panicked human negotiation of verses 1-12 and the confident, specific divine oracle of verse 13 is the chapter's opening argument: the crisis that looks beyond human solution is precisely the situation the LORD enters to declare Himself."
