          "body": "Read as a whole, 1 Kings 20 presents a coherent and sobering theology of divine grace. The LORD delivers Israel through Ahab not because Ahab is faithful (he is a Baal-worshiper), not because Israel is righteous (the nation is deep in apostasy), but because He intends to be *known* — to demonstrate His sovereignty over Aram's military, Aram's gods, and Aram's theology. This is grace in its most rigorous Old Testament sense: unilateral, purposeful, self-declaratory. The same chapter that contains these acts of stunning deliverance closes with a death sentence precisely because Ahab received that grace as political raw material rather than as encounter with the living God. Calvin's principle — that God's benefits carry with them a corresponding obligation of acknowledgment — is enacted narratively here. Where the grace is greatest and the knowledge of the LORD most explicitly demanded, the failure to respond in obedient fear is most severely judged. The chapter anticipates the next chapter: Ahab will go from sullen over a death sentence to murderous over a vineyard (21:1-16), a trajectory that runs consistently from the squandered grace of chapter 20 to the final verdict of Elijah in chapter 21."
