        "number": 2,
        "title": "A God of mountains and valleys — the second battle and the refutation of territorial theology (20:22-29)",
        "range": "20:22-29",
        "excerpt": "Thus says the LORD, 'Because the Arameans have said, \"The LORD is a god of the mountains, but He is not a god of the valleys,\" therefore I will give all this great multitude into your hand, and you shall know that I am the LORD.'",
        "body": "Between the two battles, the narrator gives the reader access to Aram's war council (20:23-25). The analysis is theologically honest by ANE standards: Israel's God fought them on mountainous terrain and won; therefore He is a mountain deity; fight Israel on the plain where their God has no jurisdiction. This was standard ancient Near Eastern theology — gods were territorial, tutelary deities bound to particular landscapes, peoples, or cities. Baal was a storm deity; Hadad (Ben-hadad's namesake) was a storm and rain deity; the god of a city could be neutralized by drawing battle away from his city. The advisors are not being foolish by their own framework; they are being internally consistent.\n\nThe LORD's response is to take their theological claim seriously enough to disprove it on their chosen ground. The second oracle (20:28) explicitly quotes their theology and makes it the reason for the second defeat: *because* they have said this, *therefore* I will deliver them. God answers blasphemous theology not with argument but with historical demonstration. The 100,000 killed in one day on the plain of Aphek is the counter-argument to Aram's war council. The wall of Aphek falling on 27,000 more is the exclamation point.\n\nThe theological principle being established is enormous in its canonical reach. The God of Israel is not a local deity, not geographically bounded, not confined to the highlands of Canaan. The same LORD who rules the mountains rules the valleys, the plains, the coastal cities, the river basins of Mesopotamia, and the delta of Egypt. This is proto-monotheism pressed into military narrative: there is only one God, and no terrain is outside His sovereignty. Isaiah will make the same argument against the Assyrians (Isaiah 37:22-29); Jeremiah will make it against Babylon. Kings makes it here against Aram, narratively, before the prophets develop it doctrinally.\n\nThe seven-day encampment before the battle (20:29) is a further deliberate marker. Seven is Israel's liturgical number — Jericho's seven days (Joshua 6:4), creation's seven days, the seventh day as Sabbath. The narrator signals that this battle is the LORD's, fought on His timetable, not Aram's or Ahab's. And when it is joined on the seventh day, the slaughter is disproportionate to any human explanation.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Elohei harim* (gods of the mountains) — plural *elohim* applied to the LORD by Aram, reflecting their polytheistic frame. The LORD appropriates their language and refutes it. *Mishor* (plain) — the flat terrain where chariotry had maximum advantage; Israel had no comparable chariot force. *Sheva yamim* (seven days) — the liturgical marker the narrator uses deliberately."
